^*BDirect 1N Overcall^*N:
Requires 15-18 HCP—a little more than 1N open—and stoppers for the opener's suit(s). In ^*Bbalancing NT^*N seat, the typical range is 11-14 (some play 10-13 or 10-14). To respond to both, many partnerships use ^*BSystem on - Double Stolen Bid^*N which what we address here. Other approaches are outside the scope of this short presentation. First a few simple observations.|PG||AT|

Opening notrump bids put the partnership in very familiar territory. Responder has an accurate picture of opener’s strength and distribution, making it easy to decide both HOW HIGH and WHERE the partnership belongs. Responder also has tools such as Stayman, Jacoby transfer to majors, and transfer to minors bids to help out. Similarly, when the opponents open the bidding we want to keep our notrump structure intact whenever possible. We can do that well, but with a few adjustments here and there. |PG||AT|
 
Why a direct overcall of 1NT needs a little higher—18 points or so. Because it’s more dangerous to overcall 1NT than to open 1NT. Our left-hand opponent is in a better position to make a penalty double if the deal belongs to their side. The opening bid has shown some strength and given an indication of the best opening lead. So we’d like a little extra when we come into the fray.

The other difference from the 1NT opening bid is that we need one or more stoppers—high cards and length—in opener's suit. This is because our left-hand opponent now has a good idea what to lead, especially if the opening bid is in a major, promising five or more cards.|PG||AT|

Double of a 1NT opening bid, almost universally, is for penalty and the opening bidder will usually choose to defend except with a very distributional hand. However, many modern partnerships prefer to use it as a conventional takeout. |PG||AT|

Let us look at a few examples. Please click the blue "Next Page" top right to begin.|PG||NT||
